# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lora-peft
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] In machine learning, **backpropagation** is a gradient computation method commonly used for training a neural network in computing parameter updates.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] It is an efficient application of the chain rule to neural networks.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Backpropagation efficiently computes the gradient of the loss with respect to the network weights for a single input–output example.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] It does this by propagating derivatives backward, one layer at a time, from the output layer to the input layer, thereby avoiding redundant chain-rule calculations.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Strictly speaking, the term *backpropagation* refers only to an algorithm for efficiently computing the gradient, not how the gradient is used, but the term is often used loosely to refer to the entire learning algorithm.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] This includes changing model parameters in the negative direction of the gradient, such as by stochastic gradient descent, or as an intermediate step in a more complicated optimizer, such as Adaptive Moment Estimation.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Backpropagation had multiple discoveries and partial discoveries, with a tangled history and terminology (see § History).
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Some other names for the technique include "reverse mode of automatic differentiation" or "reverse accumulation".
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Backpropagation computes the gradient in weight space of a feedforward neural network, with respect to a loss function.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] In the derivation of backpropagation, other intermediate quantities are used by introducing them as needed below.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Bias terms are not treated specially since they correspond to a weight with a fixed input of 1.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] For backpropagation the specific loss function and activation functions do not matter as long as they and their derivatives can be evaluated efficiently.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Traditional activation functions include sigmoid, tanh, ReLU, Swish, Mish, and many others.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] For a training set there will be a set of input–output pairs, $\left\{(x_{i},y_{i})\right\}$ .
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Note the distinction: during model evaluation the weights are fixed while the inputs vary (and the target output may be unknown), and the network ends with the output layer (it does not include the loss function).
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] During model training the input–output pair is fixed while the weights vary, and the network ends with the loss function.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Backpropagation computes the gradient for a *fixed* input–output pair $(x_{i},y_{i})$ , where the weights $w_{jk}^{l}$ can vary.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Each individual component of the gradient, $\partial C/\partial w_{jk}^{l},$ can be computed by the chain rule; but doing this separately for each weight is inefficient.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Backpropagation efficiently computes the gradient by avoiding duplicate calculations and not computing unnecessary intermediate values, by computing the gradient of each layer – specifically the gradient of the weighted *input* of each layer, denoted by $\delta ^{l}$ – from back to front.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] First, it avoids duplication because when computing the gradient at layer l , it is unnecessary to recompute all derivatives on later layers $l+1,l+2,\ldots$ each time.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Backpropagation can be expressed for simple feedforward networks in terms of matrix multiplication, or more generally in terms of the adjoint graph.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] To compute this, one starts with the input x and works forward; denote the weighted input of each hidden layer as $z^{l}$ and the output of hidden layer l as the activation $a^{l}$ .
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] For backpropagation, the activation $a^{l}$ as well as the derivatives $(f^{l})'$ (evaluated at $z^{l}$ ) must be cached for use during the backwards pass.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Note that $\delta ^{l}$ is a vector, of length equal to the number of nodes in level l ; each component is interpreted as the "cost attributable to (the value of) that node".
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The factor of $a^{l-1}$ is because the weights $W^{l}$ between level $l-1$ and l affect level l proportionally to the inputs (activations): the inputs are fixed, the weights vary.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The gradients of the weights can thus be computed using a few matrix multiplications for each level; this is backpropagation.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Multiplying starting from $\nabla _{a^{L}}C$ – propagating the error *backwards* – means that each step simply multiplies a vector ( $\delta ^{l}$ ) by the matrices of weights $(W^{l})^{T}$ and derivatives of activations $(f^{l-1})'$ .
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] By contrast, multiplying forwards, starting from the changes at an earlier layer, means that each multiplication multiplies a *matrix* by a *matrix*.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] For more general graphs, and other advanced variations, backpropagation can be understood in terms of automatic differentiation, where backpropagation is a special case of reverse accumulation (or "reverse mode").
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The goal of any supervised learning algorithm is to find a function that best maps a set of inputs to their correct output.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The motivation for backpropagation is to train a multi-layered neural network such that it can learn the appropriate internal representations to allow it to learn any arbitrary mapping of input to output.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] To understand the mathematical derivation of the backpropagation algorithm, it helps to first develop some intuition about the relationship between the actual output of a neuron and the correct output for a particular training example.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Consider a simple neural network with two input units, one output unit and no hidden units, and in which each neuron uses a linear output (unlike most work on neural networks, in which mapping from inputs to outputs is non-linear) that is the weighted sum of its input.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Initially, before training, the weights will be set randomly.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Then the neuron learns from training examples, which in this case consist of a set of tuples $(x_{1},x_{2},t)$ where $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ are the inputs to the network and t is the correct output (the output the network should produce given those inputs, when it has been trained).
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The initial network, given $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ , will compute an output y that likely differs from t (given random weights).
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] A loss function $L(t,y)$ is used for measuring the discrepancy between the target output t and the computed output y.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] For regression analysis problems the squared error can be used as a loss function, for classification the categorical cross-entropy can be used.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Consider the network on a single training case: $(1,1,0)$ .
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Thus, the input $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ are 1 and 1 respectively and the correct output, t is 0.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Now if the relation is plotted between the network's output y on the horizontal axis and the error E on the vertical axis, the result is a parabola.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The minimum of the parabola corresponds to the output y which minimizes the error E.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] For a single training case, the minimum also touches the horizontal axis, which means the error will be zero and the network can produce an output y that exactly matches the target output t.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Therefore, the problem of mapping inputs to outputs can be reduced to an optimization problem of finding a function that will produce the minimal error.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] where $w_{1}$ and $w_{2}$ are the weights on the connection from the input units to the output unit.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Therefore, the error also depends on the incoming weights to the neuron, which is ultimately what needs to be changed in the network to enable learning.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Then, the loss function E takes the form of a parabolic cylinder with its base directed along $w_{1}=-w_{2}$ .
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Since all sets of weights that satisfy $w_{1}=-w_{2}$ minimize the loss function, in this case additional constraints are required to converge to a unique solution.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Additional constraints could either be generated by setting specific conditions to the weights, or by injecting additional training data.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] One commonly used algorithm to find the set of weights that minimizes the error is gradient descent.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] By backpropagation, the steepest descent direction is calculated of the loss function versus the present synaptic weights.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Then, the weights can be modified along the steepest descent direction, and the error is minimized in an efficient way.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The gradient descent method involves calculating the derivative of the loss function with respect to the weights of the network.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] This is normally done using backpropagation.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] is the actual output of the output neuron.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] In this section, the order of the weight indexes are reversed relative to the prior section: $w_{ij}$ is weight from the i th to the j th unit.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] where the activation function $\varphi$ is non-linear and differentiable over the activation region (the ReLU is not differentiable at one point).
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The input ${\text{net}}_{j}$ to a neuron is the weighted sum of outputs $o_{k}$ of previous neurons.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] If the neuron is in the first layer after the input layer, the $o_{k}$ of the input layer are simply the inputs $x_{k}$ to the network.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The number of input units to the neuron is n .
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The variable $w_{kj}$ denotes the weight between neuron k of the previous layer and neuron j of the current layer.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] If the neuron is in the first layer after the input layer, $o_{i}$ is just $x_{i}$ .
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] This is the reason why backpropagation requires that the activation function be differentiable.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] However, if j is in an arbitrary inner layer of the network, finding the derivative E with respect to $o_{j}$ is less obvious.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] To update the weight $w_{ij}$ using gradient descent, one must choose a learning rate, $\eta >0$ .
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The change in weight needs to reflect the impact on E of an increase or decrease in $w_{ij}$ .
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] If ${\frac {\partial E}{\partial w_{ij}}}>0$ , an increase in $w_{ij}$ increases E ; conversely, if ${\frac {\partial E}{\partial w_{ij}}}<0$ , an increase in $w_{ij}$ decreases E .
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The new $\Delta w_{ij}$ is added to the old weight, and the product of the learning rate and the gradient, multiplied by $-1$ guarantees that $w_{ij}$ changes in a way that always decreases E .
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Using a Hessian matrix of second-order derivatives of the error function, the Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm often converges faster than first-order gradient descent, especially when the topology of the error function is complicated.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] It may also find solutions in smaller node counts for which other methods might not converge.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The Hessian can be approximated by the Fisher information matrix.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] As an example, consider a simple feedforward network.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Arbitrary-order derivatives in arbitrary computational graphs can be computed with backpropagation, but with more complex expressions for higher orders.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The loss function is a function that maps values of one or more variables onto a real number intuitively representing some "cost" associated with those values.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] For backpropagation, the loss function calculates the difference between the network output and its expected output, after a training example has propagated through the network.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The mathematical expression of the loss function must fulfill two conditions in order for it to be possibly used in backpropagation.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The first is that it can be written as an average ${\textstyle E={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{x}E_{x}}$ over error functions ${\textstyle E_{x}}$ , for ${\textstyle n}$ individual training examples, ${\textstyle x}$ .
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The reason for this assumption is that the backpropagation algorithm calculates the gradient of the error function for a single training example, which needs to be generalized to the overall error function.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The second assumption is that it can be written as a function of the outputs from the neural network.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Select an error function $E(y,y')$ measuring the difference between two outputs.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Backpropagation had been derived repeatedly, as it is essentially an efficient application of the chain rule (first written down by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1676) to neural networks.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The terminology "back-propagating error correction" was introduced in 1962 by Frank Rosenblatt, but he did not know how to implement this.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] In any case, he only studied neurons whose outputs were discrete levels, which only had zero derivatives, making backpropagation impossible.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Precursors to backpropagation appeared in optimal control theory since 1950s.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Yann LeCun et al credits 1950s work by Pontryagin and others in optimal control theory, especially the adjoint state method, for being a continuous-time version of backpropagation.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Hecht-Nielsen credits the Robbins–Monro algorithm (1951) and Arthur Bryson and Yu-Chi Ho's *Applied Optimal Control* (1969) as presages of backpropagation.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] In 1962, Stuart Dreyfus published a simpler derivation based only on the chain rule.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] In 1973, he adapted parameters of controllers in proportion to error gradients.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Unlike modern backpropagation, these precursors used standard Jacobian matrix calculations from one stage to the previous one, neither addressing direct links across several stages nor potential additional efficiency gains due to network sparsity.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The ADALINE (1960) learning algorithm was gradient descent with a squared error loss for a single layer.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The first multilayer perceptron (MLP) with more than one layer trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The MLP had 5 layers, with 2 learnable layers, and it learned to classify patterns not linearly separable.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Modern backpropagation was first published by Seppo Linnainmaa as "reverse mode of automatic differentiation" (1970) for discrete connected networks of nested differentiable functions.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] In 1982, Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to MLPs in the way that has become standard.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Werbos described how he developed backpropagation in an interview.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] In 1971, during his PhD work, he developed backpropagation to mathematicize Freud's "flow of psychic energy".
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] He faced repeated difficulty in publishing the work, only managing in 1981.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] He also claimed that "the first practical application of back-propagation was for estimating a dynamic model to predict nationalism and social communications in 1974" by him.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Rumelhart independently developed backpropagation and taught the algorithm to others in his research circle.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] He did not cite previous work as he was unaware of them.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] He published the algorithm first in a 1985 paper, then in a 1986 *Nature* paper an experimental analysis of the technique.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] These papers became highly cited, contributed to the popularization of backpropagation, and coincided with the resurging research interest in neural networks during the 1980s.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] In 1985, the method was also described by David Parker.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Yann LeCun proposed an alternative form of backpropagation for neural networks in his PhD thesis in 1987.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Gradient descent took a considerable amount of time to reach acceptance.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Some early objections were: there were no guarantees that gradient descent could reach a global minimum, only local minimum; neurons were "known" by physiologists as making discrete signals (0/1), not continuous ones, and with discrete signals, there is no gradient to take.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] See the interview with Geoffrey Hinton, who was awarded the 2024 Nobel Prize in Physics for his contributions to the field.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Contributing to the acceptance were several applications in training neural networks via backpropagation, sometimes achieving popularity outside the research circles.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] In 1987, NETtalk learned to convert English text into pronunciation.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Sejnowski tried training it with both backpropagation and Boltzmann machine, but found the backpropagation significantly faster, so he used it for the final NETtalk.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The NETtalk program became a popular success, appearing on the *Today* show.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Pomerleau published ALVINN, a neural network trained to drive autonomously using backpropagation.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] The LeNet was published in 1989 to recognize handwritten zip codes.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] In 1992, TD-Gammon achieved top human level play in backgammon.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] It was a reinforcement learning agent with a neural network with two layers, trained by backpropagation.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] In 1993, Eric Wan won an international pattern recognition contest through backpropagation.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] During the 2000s it fell out of favour, but returned in the 2010s, benefiting from cheap, powerful GPU-based computing systems.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] Error backpropagation has been suggested to explain human brain event-related potential (ERP) components like the N400 and P600.
[src:lora-peft/backpropagation] In 2023, a backpropagation algorithm was implemented on a photonic processor by a team at Stanford University.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] In deep learning, **fine-tuning** is the process of adapting a computational model trained for one task (the *upstream task*) to perform a different, usually more specific, task (the *downstream task*).
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] It is considered a form of transfer learning, as it reuses knowledge learned from the original training objective.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning involves applying additional training (e.g., on new data) to the parameters of a neural network that have been pre-trained.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] The additional training can be applied to the entire neural network, or to only a subset of its layers, in which case the layers that are not being fine-tuned are "frozen" (i.e., not changed during backpropagation).
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] A model may also be augmented with "adapters"—lightweight modules inserted into the model's architecture that nudge the embedding space for domain adaptation.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] These contain far fewer parameters than the original model and can be fine-tuned in a parameter-efficient way by tuning only their weights and leaving the rest of the model's weights frozen.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Models that are pre-trained on large, general corpora are usually fine-tuned by reusing their parameters as a starting point and adding a task-specific layer trained from scratch.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning the full model is also common and often yields better results, but is more computationally expensive.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning is typically accomplished via supervised learning, but there are also techniques to fine-tune a model using weak supervision.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning can be combined with a reinforcement learning from human feedback-based objective to produce language models such as ChatGPT (a fine-tuned version of GPT models) and Sparrow.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning can degrade a model's robustness to distribution shifts.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] One mitigation is to linearly interpolate a fine-tuned model's weights with the weights of the original model, which can greatly increase out-of-distribution performance while largely retaining the in-distribution performance of the fine-tuned model.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Low-rank adaptation (LoRA) is an adapter-based technique for efficiently fine-tuning models.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] The basic idea is to design a low-rank matrix that is then added to the original matrix.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] An adapter, in this context, is a collection of low-rank matrices which, when added to a base model, produces a fine-tuned model.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] It allows for performance that approaches full-model fine-tuning with lower space requirements.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] A language model with billions of parameters may be LoRA fine-tuned with only several millions of parameters.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] LoRA-based fine-tuning has become popular in the Stable Diffusion community.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Support for LoRA was integrated into the diffusers library from Hugging Face.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Support for LoRA and similar techniques is also available for a wide range of other models through Hugging Face's *parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT)* package.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Representation fine-tuning (ReFT) is a technique developed by researchers at Stanford University aimed at fine-tuning large language models (LLMs) by modifying less than 1% of their representations.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Unlike parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT) methods, which mainly focus on updating weights, ReFT targets representations.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] ReFT methods operate on a frozen base model and learn task-specific interventions on hidden representations and train interventions that manipulate a small fraction of model representations to steer model behaviors towards solving downstream tasks at inference time.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] One specific method within the ReFT family is low-rank linear subspace ReFT (LoReFT), which intervenes on hidden representations in the linear subspace spanned by a low-rank projection matrix.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] LoReFT can be seen as the representation-based equivalent of low-rank adaptation (LoRA).
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning is common in natural language processing (NLP), especially in the domain of language modeling.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Large language models like OpenAI's series of GPT foundation models can be fine-tuned on data for specific downstream NLP tasks (tasks that use a pre-trained model) to improve performance over the unmodified pre-trained model.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Platforms such as Semrush's *AI Visibility Toolkit* and *Enterprise AIO* exemplify how fine-tuned models are being used for entity-level monitoring; tracking how named entities are referenced and represented within responses generated by large-language-model-based answer engines.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Commercially-offered large language models can sometimes be fine-tuned if the provider offers a fine-tuning API.
[src:lora-peft/fine-tuning-deep-learning] As of June 19, 2023, language model fine-tuning APIs are offered by OpenAI and Microsoft Azure's Azure OpenAI Service for a subset of their models, as well as by Google Cloud Platform for some of their PaLM models, and by others.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:lora-peft/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] In linear algebra, the **rank** of a matrix A is the dimension of the vector space generated (or spanned) by its columns.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] This corresponds to the maximal number of linearly independent columns of A.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] This, in turn, is identical to the dimension of the vector space spanned by its rows.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Rank is thus a measure of the "nondegenerateness" of the system of linear equations and linear transformation encoded by A.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] There are multiple equivalent definitions of rank.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] A matrix's rank is one of its most fundamental characteristics.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The rank is commonly denoted by rank(*A*) or rk(*A*); sometimes the parentheses are not written, as in rank *A*.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The rank can also be denoted by rg(*A*), from German *Rang*.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] More generally, the rank of a linear map between two vector spaces is the dimension of its image.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] In this section, we give some definitions of the rank of a matrix.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Many definitions are possible; see Alternative definitions for several of these.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The **column rank** of A is the dimension of the column space of A, while the **row rank** of A is the dimension of the row space of A.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] A fundamental result in linear algebra is that the column rank and the row rank are always equal.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] (Three proofs of this result are given in § Proofs that column rank = row rank, below.) This number (i.e., the number of linearly independent rows or columns) is simply called the **rank** of A.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] A matrix is said to have **full rank** if its rank equals the largest possible for a matrix of the same dimensions, which is the lesser of the number of rows and columns.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] A matrix is said to be **rank-deficient** if it does not have full rank.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The **rank deficiency** of a matrix is the difference between the lesser of the number of rows and columns, and the rank.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The rank of a linear map or operator $\Phi$ is defined as the dimension of its image: $\operatorname {rank} (\Phi ):=\dim(\operatorname {img} (\Phi ))$ where $\dim$ is the dimension of a vector space, and $\operatorname {img}$ is the image of a map.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The matrix $A={\begin{bmatrix}1&1&0&2\\-1&-1&0&-2\end{bmatrix}}$ has rank 1: there are nonzero columns, so the rank is positive, but any pair of columns is linearly dependent.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Indeed, since the column vectors of A are the row vectors of the transpose of A, the statement that the column rank of a matrix equals its row rank is equivalent to the statement that the rank of a matrix is equal to the rank of its transpose, i.e., rank(*A*) = rank(*A*T).
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] A common approach to finding the rank of a matrix is to reduce it to a simpler form, generally row echelon form, by elementary row operations.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Row operations do not change the row space (hence do not change the row rank), and, being invertible, map the column space to an isomorphic space (hence do not change the column rank).
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Once in row echelon form, the rank is clearly the same for both row rank and column rank, and equals the number of pivots (or basic columns) and also the number of non-zero rows.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] When applied to floating point computations on computers, basic Gaussian elimination (LU decomposition) can be unreliable, and a rank-revealing decomposition should be used instead.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] An effective alternative is the singular value decomposition (SVD), but there are other less computationally expensive choices, such as QR decomposition with pivoting (so-called rank-revealing QR factorization), which are still more numerically robust than Gaussian elimination.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Numerical determination of rank requires a criterion for deciding when a value, such as a singular value from the SVD, should be treated as zero, a practical choice which depends on both the matrix and the application.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The fact that the column and row ranks of any matrix are equal is fundamental in linear algebra.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] One of the most elementary ones has been sketched in § Rank from row echelon forms.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] It is straightforward to show that neither the row rank nor the column rank are changed by an elementary row operation.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] As Gaussian elimination proceeds by elementary row operations, the reduced row echelon form of a matrix has the same row rank and the same column rank as the original matrix.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Further elementary column operations allow putting the matrix in the form of an identity matrix possibly bordered by rows and columns of zeros.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Again, this changes neither the row rank nor the column rank.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] It is immediate that both the row and column ranks of this resulting matrix is the number of its nonzero entries.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] We present two other proofs of this result.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The first uses only basic properties of linear combinations of vectors, and is valid over any field.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The second uses orthogonality and is valid for matrices over the real numbers; it is based upon Mackiw (1995).
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Both proofs can be found in the book by Banerjee and Roy (2014).
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Let the column rank of A be r, and let **c**1, ..., **c***r* be any basis for the column space of A.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Place these as the columns of an *m* × *r* matrix C.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Every column of A can be expressed as a linear combination of the r columns in C.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] This means that there is an *r* × *n* matrix R such that *A* = *CR*.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] R is the matrix whose ith column is formed from the coefficients giving the ith column of A as a linear combination of the r columns of C.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] In other words, R is the matrix which contains the multiples for the bases of the column space of A (which is C), which are then used to form A as a whole.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Now, each row of A is given by a linear combination of the r rows of R.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Therefore, the rows of R form a spanning set of the row space of A and, by the Steinitz exchange lemma, the row rank of A cannot exceed r.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] This proves that the row rank of A is less than or equal to the column rank of A.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] This result can be applied to any matrix, so apply the result to the transpose of A.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Since the row rank of the transpose of A is the column rank of A and the column rank of the transpose of A is the row rank of A, this establishes the reverse inequality and we obtain the equality of the row rank and the column rank of A.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Let A be an *m* × *n* matrix with entries in the real numbers whose row rank is r.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Therefore, the dimension of the row space of A is r.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] We make two observations: (a) **v** is a linear combination of vectors in the row space of A, which implies that **v** belongs to the row space of A, and (b) since *A***v** = 0, the vector **v** is orthogonal to every row vector of A and, hence, is orthogonal to every vector in the row space of A.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Every *A***x***i* is in the column space of A.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] So, *A***x**1, *A***x**2, ..., *A***x***r* is a set of r linearly independent vectors in the column space of A and, hence, the dimension of the column space of A (i.e., the column rank of A) must be at least as big as r.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] This proves that row rank of A is no larger than the column rank of A.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Now apply this result to the transpose of A to get the reverse inequality and conclude as in the previous proof.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] In all the definitions in this section, the matrix A is taken to be an *m* × *n* matrix over an arbitrary field F.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Given the matrix A , there is an associated linear mapping $f:F^{n}\to F^{m}$ defined by $f(x)=Ax.$ The rank of A is the dimension of the image of f .
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] This definition has the advantage that it can be applied to any linear map without need for a specific matrix.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Given the same linear mapping f as above, the rank is n minus the dimension of the kernel of f.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The rank–nullity theorem states that this definition is equivalent to the preceding one.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The rank of A is the maximal number of linearly independent rows of A; this is the dimension of the row space of A.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The rank of A is the smallest positive integer k such that A can be factored as $A=CR$ , where C is an *m* × *k* matrix and R is a *k* × *n* matrix.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] 5. the row rank of A is less than or equal to k.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Indeed, the following equivalences are obvious: $(1)\Leftrightarrow (2)\Leftrightarrow (3)\Leftrightarrow (4)\Leftrightarrow (5)$ .
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] For example, to prove (3) from (2), take C to be the matrix whose columns are $\mathbf {c} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {c} _{k}$ from (2).
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] To prove (2) from (3), take $\mathbf {c} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {c} _{k}$ to be the columns of C.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] It follows from the equivalence $(1)\Leftrightarrow (5)$ that the row rank is equal to the column rank.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Unfortunately, this definition does not suggest an efficient manner to compute the rank (for which it is better to use one of the alternative definitions).
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The rank of A equals the number of non-zero singular values, which is the same as the number of non-zero diagonal elements in Σ in the singular value decomposition $A=U\Sigma V^{*}$ .
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The rank of A is the largest order of any non-zero minor in A.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The rank of A is the smallest number k such that A can be written as a sum of k rank 1 matrices, where a matrix is defined to have rank 1 if and only if it can be written as a nonzero product $c\cdot r$ of a column vector c and a row vector r.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] This notion of rank is called tensor rank; it can be generalized in the separable models interpretation of the singular value decomposition.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] We assume that A is an *m* × *n* matrix, and we define the linear map f by *f*(**x**) = *A***x** as above.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] This is a special case of the next inequality.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] , each have only the zero vector in common.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] One useful application of calculating the rank of a matrix is the computation of the number of solutions of a system of linear equations.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] According to the Rouché–Capelli theorem, the system is inconsistent if the rank of the augmented matrix is greater than the rank of the coefficient matrix.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] If on the other hand, the ranks of these two matrices are equal, then the system must have at least one solution.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The solution is unique if and only if the rank equals the number of variables.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Otherwise the general solution has k free parameters where k is the difference between the number of variables and the rank.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] In this case (and assuming the system of equations is in the real or complex numbers) the system of equations has infinitely many solutions.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] In control theory, the rank of a matrix can be used to determine whether a linear system is controllable, or observable.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] In the field of communication complexity, the rank of the communication matrix of a function gives bounds on the amount of communication needed for two parties to compute the function.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] There are different generalizations of the concept of rank to matrices over arbitrary rings, where column rank, row rank, dimension of column space, and dimension of row space of a matrix may be different from the others or may not exist.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Thinking of matrices as tensors, the tensor rank generalizes to arbitrary tensors; for tensors of order greater than 2 (matrices are order 2 tensors), rank is very hard to compute, unlike for matrices.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] There is a notion of rank for smooth maps between smooth manifolds.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] It is equal to the linear rank of the derivative.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Matrix rank should not be confused with tensor order, which is called tensor rank.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] Tensor order is the number of indices required to write a tensor, and thus matrices all have tensor order 2.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] More precisely, matrices are tensors of type (1,1), having one row index and one column index, also called covariant order 1 and contravariant order 1; see Tensor (intrinsic definition) for details.
[src:lora-peft/rank-linear-algebra] The tensor rank of a matrix can also mean the minimum number of simple tensors necessary to express the matrix as a linear combination, and that this definition does agree with matrix rank as here discussed.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] In mathematics, statistics, finance, and computer science, particularly in machine learning and inverse problems, **regularization** is a process that converts the answer to a problem to a simpler one.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] It is often used in solving ill-posed problems or to prevent overfitting.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] There is a strong connection between regularization methods and Bayesian approaches for solving such ill-posed problems .
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] In explicit regularization, independent of the problem or model, there is always a data term, that corresponds to a likelihood of the measurement, and a regularization term that corresponds to a prior.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] By combining both using Bayesian statistics, one can compute a posterior, that includes both information sources and therefore stabilizes the estimation process.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] By trading off both objectives, one chooses to be more aligned to the data or to enforce regularization (to prevent overfitting).
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] There is a whole research branch dealing with all possible regularizations.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] In practice, one usually tries a specific regularization and then figures out the probability density that corresponds to that regularization to justify the choice.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] It can also be physically motivated by common sense or intuition.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] In machine learning, the data term corresponds to the training data and the regularization is either the choice of the model or modifications to the algorithm.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] It is always intended to reduce the generalization error, i.e. the error score with the trained model on the evaluation set (testing data) and not the training data.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] One of the earliest uses of regularization is Tikhonov regularization (ridge regression), related to the method of least squares.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] In machine learning, a key challenge is enabling models to accurately predict outcomes on unseen data, not just on familiar training data.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Regularization is crucial for addressing overfitting—where a model memorizes training data details but cannot generalize to new data.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The goal of regularization is to encourage models to learn the broader patterns within the data rather than memorizing it.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Techniques like early stopping, L1 and L2 regularization, and dropout are designed to prevent overfitting and underfitting, thereby enhancing the model's ability to adapt to and perform well with new data, thus improving model generalization.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Stops training when validation performance deteriorates, preventing overfitting by halting before the model memorizes training data.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] In the context of neural networks, the Dropout technique repeatedly ignores random subsets of neurons during training, which simulates the training of multiple neural network architectures at once to improve generalization.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Empirical learning of classifiers (from a finite data set) is always an underdetermined problem, because it attempts to infer a function of any x given only examples $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}$ .
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Concrete notions of complexity used include restrictions for smoothness and bounds on the vector space norm.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] A theoretical justification for regularization is that it attempts to impose Occam's razor on the solution (as depicted in the figure above, where the green function, the simpler one, may be preferred).
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] From a Bayesian point of view, many regularization techniques correspond to imposing certain prior distributions on model parameters.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Regularization can serve multiple purposes, including learning simpler models, inducing models to be sparse and introducing group structure into the learning problem.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The same idea arose in many fields of science.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] A simple form of regularization applied to integral equations (Tikhonov regularization) is essentially a trade-off between fitting the data and reducing a norm of the solution.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] More recently, non-linear regularization methods, including total variation regularization, have become popular.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Regularization can be motivated as a technique to improve the generalizability of a learned model.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The goal of this learning problem is to find a function that fits or predicts the outcome (label) that minimizes the expected error over all possible inputs and labels.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The expected error of a function $f_{n}$ is: $I[f_{n}]=\int _{X\times Y}V(f_{n}(x),y)\rho (x,y)\,dx\,dy$ where X and Y are the domains of input data x and their labels y respectively.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Typically in learning problems, only a subset of input data and labels are available, measured with some noise.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] If measurements (e.g. of $x_{i}$ ) were made with noise, this model may suffer from overfitting and display poor expected error.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Regularization introduces a penalty for exploring certain regions of the function space used to build the model, which can improve generalization.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] These techniques are named for Andrey Nikolayevich Tikhonov, who applied regularization to integral equations and made important contributions in many other areas.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] When learning a linear function f , characterized by an unknown vector w such that $f(x)=w\cdot x$ , one can add the $L_{2}$ -norm of the vector w to the loss expression in order to prefer solutions with smaller norms.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Tikhonov regularization is one of the most common forms.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] As the $L_{2}$ norm is differentiable, learning can be advanced by gradient descent.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The learning problem with the least squares loss function and Tikhonov regularization can be solved analytically.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] By construction of the optimization problem, other values of w give larger values for the loss function.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] This can be verified by examining the second derivative $\nabla _{ww}$ .
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] During training, this algorithm takes $O(d^{3}+nd^{2})$ time.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The terms correspond to the matrix inversion and calculating $X^{\mathsf {T}}X$ , respectively.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Early stopping can be viewed as regularization in time.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Intuitively, a training procedure such as gradient descent tends to learn more and more complex functions with increasing iterations.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] By regularizing for time, model complexity can be controlled, improving generalization.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Early stopping is implemented using one data set for training, one statistically independent data set for validation and another for testing.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The model is trained until performance on the validation set no longer improves and then applied to the test set.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The exact solution to the unregularized least squares learning problem minimizes the empirical error, but may fail.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] By limiting T, the only free parameter in the algorithm above, the problem is regularized for time, which may improve its generalization.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Enforcing a sparsity constraint on w can lead to simpler and more interpretable models.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] This is useful in many real-life applications such as computational biology.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] An example is developing a simple predictive test for a disease in order to minimize the cost of performing medical tests while maximizing predictive power.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] A sensible sparsity constraint is the $L_{0}$ norm $\|w\|_{0}$ , defined as the number of non-zero elements in w .
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Solving a $L_{0}$ regularized learning problem, however, has been demonstrated to be NP-hard.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The $L_{1}$ norm (see also Norms) can be used to approximate the optimal $L_{0}$ norm via convex relaxation.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] It can be shown that the $L_{1}$ norm induces sparsity.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] $L_{1}$ regularization can occasionally produce non-unique solutions.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] A simple example is provided in the figure when the space of possible solutions lies on a 45 degree line.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Elastic net regularization tends to have a grouping effect, where correlated input features are assigned equal weights.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Elastic net regularization is commonly used in practice and is implemented in many machine learning libraries.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] While the $L_{1}$ norm does not result in an NP-hard problem, the $L_{1}$ norm is convex but is not strictly differentiable due to the kink at x = 0.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Subgradient methods which rely on the subderivative can be used to solve $L_{1}$ regularized learning problems.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] However, faster convergence can be achieved through proximal methods.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] For a problem $\min _{w\in H}F(w)+R(w)$ such that F is convex, continuous, differentiable, with Lipschitz continuous gradient (such as the least squares loss function), and R is convex, continuous, and proper, then the proximal method to solve the problem is as follows.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The proximal method iteratively performs gradient descent and then projects the result back into the space permitted by R .
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Groups of features can be regularized by a sparsity constraint, which can be useful for expressing certain prior knowledge into an optimization problem.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] This can be viewed as inducing a regularizer over the $L_{2}$ norm over members of each group followed by an $L_{1}$ norm over groups.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The algorithm described for group sparsity without overlaps can be applied to the case where groups do overlap, in certain situations.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] This will likely result in some groups with all zero elements, and other groups with some non-zero and some zero elements.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] For each $w_{g}$ , ${\bar {w}}_{g}$ is defined as the vector such that the restriction of ${\bar {w}}_{g}$ to the group g equals $w_{g}$ and all other entries of ${\bar {w}}_{g}$ are zero.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The regularizer finds the optimal disintegration of w into parts.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] It can be viewed as duplicating all elements that exist in multiple groups.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Learning problems with this regularizer can also be solved with the proximal method with a complication.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The proximal operator cannot be computed in closed form, but can be effectively solved iteratively, inducing an inner iteration within the proximal method iteration.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] When labels are more expensive to gather than input examples, semi-supervised learning can be useful.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Regularizers have been designed to guide learning algorithms to learn models that respect the structure of unsupervised training samples.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] If $W_{ij}$ encodes the result of some distance metric for points $x_{i}$ and $x_{j}$ , it is desirable that $f(x_{i})\approx f(x_{j})$ .
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] This regularizer captures this intuition, and is equivalent to: $R(f)={\bar {f}}^{\mathsf {T}}L{\bar {f}}$ where $L=D-W$ is the Laplacian matrix of the graph induced by W .
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The optimization problem $\min _{f\in \mathbb {R} ^{m}}R(f),m=u+l$ can be solved analytically if the constraint $f(x_{i})=y_{i}$ is applied for all supervised samples.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The labeled part of the vector f is therefore obvious.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] In the case of multitask learning, T problems are considered simultaneously, each related in some way.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The goal is to learn T functions, ideally borrowing strength from the relatedness of tasks, that have predictive power.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] This is equivalent to learning the matrix $W:T\times D$ .
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] This regularizer defines an L2 norm on each column and an L1 norm over all columns.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] $R(w)=\left\|\sigma (W)\right\|_{1}$ where $\sigma (W)$ is the eigenvalues in the singular value decomposition of W .
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] This regularizer constrains the functions learned for each task to be similar to the overall average of the functions across all tasks.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] This is useful for expressing prior information that each task is expected to share with each other task.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] An example is predicting blood iron levels measured at different times of the day, where each task represents an individual.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] This regularizer is similar to the mean-constrained regularizer, but instead enforces similarity between tasks within the same cluster.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] This can capture more complex prior information.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] This technique has been used to predict Netflix recommendations.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] A cluster would correspond to a group of people who share similar preferences.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] More generally than above, similarity between tasks can be defined by a function.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] The regularizer encourages the model to learn similar functions for similar tasks. $R(f_{1}\cdots f_{T})=\sum _{t,s=1,t\neq s}^{\mathsf {T}}\left\|f_{t}-f_{s}\right\|^{2}M_{ts}$ for a given symmetric similarity matrix M .
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Bayesian learning methods make use of a prior probability that (usually) gives lower probability to more complex models.
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Well-known model selection techniques include the Akaike information criterion (AIC), minimum description length (MDL), and the Bayesian information criterion (BIC).
[src:lora-peft/regularization-mathematics] Alternative methods of controlling overfitting not involving regularization include cross-validation.
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] Since transfer learning makes use of training with multiple objective functions it is related to cost-sensitive machine learning and multi-objective optimization.
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] In 1976, Bozinovski and Fulgosi published a paper addressing transfer learning in neural network training.
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] The paper gives a mathematical and geometrical model of the topic.
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] In 1981, a report considered the application of transfer learning to a dataset of images representing letters of computer terminals, experimentally demonstrating positive and negative transfer learning.
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] In 1992, Lorien Pratt formulated the discriminability-based transfer (DBT) algorithm.
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] By 1998, the field had advanced to include multi-task learning, along with more formal theoretical foundations.
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] Influential publications on transfer learning include the book *Learning to Learn* in 1998, a 2009 survey and a 2019 survey.
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] Ng said in his NIPS 2016 tutorial that TL would become the next driver of machine learning commercial success after supervised learning.
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] In the 2020 paper, "Rethinking Pre-Training and self-training", Zoph et al. reported that pre-training can hurt accuracy, and advocate self-training instead.
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] The definition of transfer learning is given in terms of domains and tasks.
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] A domain ${\mathcal {D}}$ consists of: a feature space ${\mathcal {X}}$ and a marginal probability distribution $P(X)$ , where $X=\{x_{1},...,x_{n}\}\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] Given a specific domain, ${\mathcal {D}}=\{{\mathcal {X}},P(X)\}$ , a task consists of two components: a label space ${\mathcal {Y}}$ and an objective predictive function $f:{\mathcal {X}}\rightarrow {\mathcal {Y}}$ .
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] The function f is used to predict the corresponding label $f(x)$ of a new instance x .
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] Algorithms for transfer learning are available in Markov logic networks and Bayesian networks.
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] Transfer learning has been applied to cancer subtype discovery, building utilization, general game playing, text classification, digit recognition, medical imaging and spam filtering.
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] It was noted that this relationship worked in both directions, showing that EEG brainwaves can likewise be used to classify EMG signals.
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] The experiments noted that the accuracy of neural networks and convolutional neural networks were improved through transfer learning both prior to any learning (compared to standard random weight distribution) and at the end of the learning process (asymptote).
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] That is, results are improved by exposure to another domain.
[src:lora-peft/transfer-learning] Moreover, the end-user of a pre-trained model can change the structure of fully-connected layers to improve performance.
